# gen324 (TODO.md P2, corrected) — compound assignment in the evaluator.
#
# TODO.md P2 said "the evaluator cannot execute a LOOP". That was WRONG, and the
# code refuted it: gen178 added a bounded while, gen179 a three-clause for. These
# two snippets differ by nothing but the assignment form, and only the first was
# computable:
#
#   for (i=1; i<=n; i++) { s = s + i; }   -> sum(3) = 6
#   for (i=1; i<=n; i++) { s += i; }      -> "beyond my arithmetic evaluator"
#
# The wall was never iteration. It was `+=` — the one statement almost every loop
# BODY is made of, which is why every real loop looked like a loop failure.
# Desugared to `x = x OP e`, through the SAME expression parser.

# The exact snippet from the 2026-07-12 conversation that exposed it.
> what does sum(3) return: int sum(int n){ int s=0; for(int i=0;i<=n;i++) s+=i; return s; }
< I read it as code and worked it out: sum(3) returns 6.

# Every compound operator, on held-out values.
> what does f(5) return: int f(int n){ int x=100; x -= n; return x; }
< I read it as code and worked it out: f(5) returns 95.
> what does f(3) return: int f(int n){ int x=2; x *= n; return x; }
< I read it as code and worked it out: f(3) returns 6.
> what does f(4) return: int f(int n){ int x=20; x /= n; return x; }
< I read it as code and worked it out: f(4) returns 5.
> what does f(3) return: int f(int n){ int x=10; x %= n; return x; }
< I read it as code and worked it out: f(3) returns 1.

# Composed with iteration: a factorial the answer cannot be read off the source.
> what does fact(5) return: int fact(int n){ int r=1; for(int i=2;i<=n;i++) r *= i; return r; }
< I read it as code and worked it out: fact(5) returns 120.

# A while-loop body using the same form.
> what does g(4) return: int g(int n){ int s=0; int i=1; while(i<=n){ s += i*i; i++; } return s; }
< I read it as code and worked it out: g(4) returns 30.

# HONESTY: /= and %= by zero must REFUSE, never fabricate a number. The evaluator
# latches an error and the module declines — a wrong integer would be exactly the
# fabrication gen322 was about.
> what does f(0) return: int f(int n){ int x=10; x /= n; return x; }
< I read it as code, but I cannot compute f(0) yet — its body is beyond my arithmetic evaluator.
